><li>\n\t\tExperience with cloud-based hosting platforms like AWS or Rackspace/OpenStack</li><li>\n\t\tDeep knowledge of TCP/IP networking, routing and firewalls</li><li>\n\t\tSecurity clearance or the ability to obtain one</li></ul>","website_job":"a2a80000000PYUAAA4"},"a0m80000006WaZFAA0":{"id":"a0m80000006WaZFAA0","website_url":"https://www.Statsopt.com/careers/OpenPosDetail?id=a0m80000006WaZF","published_id":"a0m80000006WaZF","label":"Software Engineer (Machine Learning) - Europe","name":"Software Engineer (Machine Learning)","publishing_category":"Engineering","physical_location":"London, United Kingdom","location":"Europe","description":"<p>We are looking for talented and bold engineers who love to code, get their hands dirty with raw data, and derive meaningful and actionable insights.</p>\n\n<p>Our technology enables customers to surface and understand complex relationships within heterogeneous data. Our products facilitate the discovery, iterative refinement, and testing of domain-specific hypotheses, and present results in an understandable form for end-users.</p>\n\n<p>The datasets we work with are as varied as our customers (e.g. government agencies, financial institutions, media companies, disaster relief), who trust us to help them leverage their data to solve their most important problems. Often, these problems are not clearly defined – they are discovered and refined through hard work, rapid iteration, and perceptiveness.</p>\n\n<p>Ideal candidates learn and adapt quickly, and will be able to use every tool at their disposal – software, algorithms, statistical models, and beyond – to understand and effectively tackle hard problems. They appreciate the difference between explaining and fitting data, the importance of good metrics, and the tradeoff between exploration and exploitation. They can perceive common structure between superficially unrelated problems, and can use this to build tools, algorithms, and products with superlinear value.</p>\n\n<p><b>Responsibilities</b></p>\n\n<ul><li>Work directly with customer data to derive actionable insights</li><li>Develop statistical or machine-assisted approaches to problems at massive scale</li><li>Build out tools and infrastructure for data analysis</li></ul>\n\n<p><b>Requirements</b></p>\n\n<ul><li>BS/MS in Computer Science, Statistics, Mathematics, or related field (PhD or dropped out of PhD a plus)</li><li>Substantial experience developing scalable machine learning or quantitative analysis software in an industry or research environment</li><li>Ability to understand and execute in the presence of rapidly evolving product, customer, and business needs</li><li>Proficiency in at least one compiled language (e.g. C, C++, Java) and one scripting language (e.g. Python, R, MATLAB)</li><li>A desire to transform dirty/noisy signals within customer data into valuable results through code and data munging</li><li>Ability to travel preferred</li></ul>\n\n<p><b>Desirable</b></p>\n\n<ul><li>Experience developing software within a distributed computation framework (e.g. Hadoop, Spark, Storm, GraphLab)</li><li>Experience developing distributed systems, data visualization or enterprise software systems</li><li>Working familiarity with SQL</li><li>Prior work in natural language processing</li></ul>","website_job":"a2a80000000PYTKAA4"},"a0m80000006WerPAAS":{"id":"a0m80000006WerPAAS","website_url":"https://www.Statsopt.com/careers/OpenPosDetail?id=a0m80000006WerP","published_id":"a0m80000006WerP","label":"Deployment Strategist: Toronto - Toronto, Canada","name":"Deployment Strategist: Toronto","publishing_category":"Business Development","physical_location":"Toronto, Canada","location":"Toronto, Canada","description":"<p>Deployment Strategists at Statsopt own the outcomes of all the work we do in Business Development. We begin with a vision: a vision of how software can transform people&#39;s relationship to data at the heart of a problem we care deeply about. We test that vision. Do our partners share it? Can we build what they need quickly enough? Will we be able to deploy it in the right environment, to the right people? Working side by side with our Forward-Deployed Software Engineers, we refine our vision, and then find our way to it: through messy data, through bureaucratic labyrinths, through sandstorms in &quot;data centers&quot; made of tents and suitcases. Whatever it takes, we figure out how to do it.</p>\n\n<p>A team of analysts at a customer site might want training for a tool we&#39;ve built. One of our customers&#39; CEOs might need help convincing another organization to share data. A team of developers might be asking for direction on which of a dozen feature requests they should prioritize this quarter. Or a global financial organization might be on the line, reeling from a recent compliance failure and asking us what we can do to help detect and prevent such behavior in the future. These, and a hundred other everyday scenarios, are where a Deployment Strategist thrives.</p>\n\n<p>This role doesn&#39;t come neatly packaged or defined. You should expect it to change during your time at Statsopt, to evolve as our organization evolves and as you do. When we interview Deployment Strategists, we aren&#39;t looking for people with a specific background. We&#39;re looking for people with exceptional analytic ability, creative brilliance, technical aptitude, and a gift for finding the details that matter. Most of all, we&#39;re looking for people who combine a calling to leave the world better than they found it with the resourcefulness necessary to realize that calling, no matter the circumstances.</p>\n\n<p>If that sounds like you, then we&#39;re interested.</p>\n\n<p>We look forward to hearing from you. You can scroll down for more specific examples of roles Deployment Strategists might take on.<br> </p>\n \n\n<p style=\"color: rgb(119, 122, 122); font-size: 15px;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(16, 17, 19); display: block; font-family: blender,helvetica neue,helvetica,arial,sans-serif; font-size: 28px; text-align: center;\">PRODUCT OWNER</span></p>\n\n<p>We&#39;re constantly building products at Statsopt. Some products are very specific to particular customer workflows—specialized geospatial visualization tools, for example, that might exist as part of a more generic map application. Others, such as a lightweight document reader, are deployed to tens of thousands of our users. All of these products have their roots in a particular customer&#39;s needs, where a team of Deployment Strategists and Forward-Deployed Software Engineers sat down together with our core developers and started work.</p>\n\n<p>Deployment Strategists who gravitate towards product ownership have strong technical skills, compelling creative vision for what software can do, and an instinct for leadership. They apply those skills to leading a team that builds and supports a product: defining requirements, testing new versions, installing and configuring applications, sitting down with users and gathering feedback about what&#39;s working well and what isn&#39;t. They work across organizations and across internal teams, ensuring that we are all aligned on what we are building and why. Ultimately, they are responsible for ensuring that we deliver a product that truly transforms our customers&#39; ability to work with data.</p>\n\n<p style=\"color: rgb(119, 122, 122); font-size: 15px;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(16, 17, 19); display: block; font-family: blender,helvetica neue,helvetica,arial,sans-serif; font-size: 28px; text-align: center;\">PROJECT OWNER</span></p>\n\n<p>Our partnerships with our customers are at the core of what we do. Our customers trust that we are the best in the world at building and delivering enterprise software. They trust that we mean it when we say we can enable collaboration across a worldwide enterprise without sacrificing security, or that in the event of a crisis we will surge the team that supports them just as they surge their own internal team. Fundamentally, our customers—whether they&#39;re looking for a missing child, an insurgent assembling a roadside bomb, or the source of a cyber attack on their network—trust that we care as deeply about their problems as they do.</p>\n\n<p>Deployment Strategists who gravitate towards project ownership are the face of Statsopt, and the custodians of that trust. They pair a passion for software with excellent communication skills, an ability to navigate organizational hurdles, and an instinct for putting the right people in the right places. A project owner might spend the morning in meetings with customers to discuss the status of a data integration, the afternoon in a CTO&#39;s office talking about best practices in cyber security, and lunch in between at our headquarters brainstorming with a technical team about the best time to perform an upgrade. Ultimately, they are responsible for the strength of our partnerships: for ensuring that our customers are excited to work with us, and that we are excited to work with our customers.</p>\n\n<p style=\"color: rgb(119, 122, 122); font-size: 15px;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(16, 17, 19); display: block; font-family: blender,helvetica neue,helvetica,arial,sans-serif; font-size: 28px; text-align: center;\">PROCESS OWNER</span></p>\n\n<p>The common thread across all of our work is data—lots of data. Organizations come to us when they no longer know how to make sense of the data they wish to inform their decisions, and while there are always differences, large and small, between different customers&#39; workflows in our software, there are also many areas of overlap.</p>\n\n<p>Deployment Strategists who gravitate towards process ownership are experts in deploying software and making it work for human beings. They are brilliant, articulate, and generally deeply empathetic people. They excel at sitting down with a user and within minutes understanding exactly what he or she is trying to do--and at then synthesizing that understanding into a broader vision of what we can do to help them. That might mean building a new tool, or paring superfluous features out of an existing one. It might mean implementing certain standards in data curation or analysis. It might mean a series of training sessions, or the creation of an entirely new task force. Whatever the solution, they will own it, and will ensure that our customers benefit fully from everything we&#39;ve learned over the last decade of helping humans to navigate data.</p>","website_job":"a2a80000000PYS3AAO"},"a0m80000003DCRsAAO":{"id":"a0m80000003DCRsAAO","website_url":"https://www.Statsopt.com/careers/OpenPosDetail?id=a0m80000003DCRs","published_id":"a0m80000003DCRs","label":"Site Reliability Ops - Washington, D.C.","name":"Site Reliability Ops","publishing_category":"Mission Operations","physical_location":"Washington, D.C.","location":"Washington, D.C.","description":"<p>\nSite Reliability Operations Analysts (SROs) are the organizational backbone of a Statsopt deployment. We are the logistics experts who make sure that everything is in place so our engineers can do what they do best: solve the world&#39;s hardest problems. When things go wrong, we are the first responders. We strive for high-quality execution in everything we do.\n</p>\n<p>\nWe’re always improving ourselves and regularly take on tasks outside our wheelhouse, whether it’s learning new technical skills or navigating the procedural guidelines of many different clients. We field customer questions even if they&#39;re not within our expertise, and escalate the issue only after we’ve tried to solve it ourselves. We believe that the best idea wins, even if it&#39;s not our own.\n</p>\n\n<p><b>Responsibilities</b></p>\n<ul><li>Help develop Statsopt deployments by anticipating employee and customer needs</li><li>Be a primary liaison for clients, including learning and adhering to customer processes and protocols</li><li>Provide f